  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GIRAgua: integrated management and efficient use of water resources in the Coquimbo region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Short general project overviewChallenge and Goal One of the main challenges for Chile is the water availability to support the economic (industry, agriculture) and urban development of the country. The current situation is not sustainable. Lack of water supply and rise of water demand are causing increasing stresses on water resources. This stress leads to quantitative, qualitative and governmental challenges.The purpose of the proposed project is to help deal with these challenges by developing a method for Integrated River Basin Management (IRBM) and to assess the feasibility applying this method to the Elqui River Basin (ERB). The understanding of the local natural water and subsurface systems in combination with water treatment technologies and best practices will be analysed, and stakeholders from various fields (including government) will be involved.&#x2022;	Initial activities and results of the projectActivities and Results- Address challenging water-related issues in Chile by looking at an entire river basin, involving all of the major stakeholders who have large water demands (mining industry, agricultural areas, urban developments), while considering both water quantity (availability) and quality issues;- Identify possible technologies and water-related practices that can be implemented to improve the current condition, including innovative technologies and practices that have been developed in the Netherlands and Chile; this will increase urban and rural resilience to climate change;- Analyse the governance and stakeholder processes at the local, regional, and national scales, and identify other gaps in scientific knowledge, governance, policy, finance, technologies, and practices that must be bridged in order to reach IRBM;- Design a pilot project that can first be applied in the ERB, Coquimbo Region, Chile; and create a methodology so that this can then be replicated in other parts of Chile and Latin America.</narrative>
  </description>
